Findings:
1. The proposed `createInvoice` function mixes three concerns in one place: HTTP transport (`NextRequest`/`NextResponse`), application behavior (approved-only invoicing and total calculation), and persistence (`prisma`). That makes the approval rule depend on Next.js and Prisma instead of the other way around.
2. The application is implicitly using Prisma result shapes as its business model. In particular, `Order` does not own `lines`; that shape only exists because of the Prisma query. For a production design, the use case should own the data shape it needs.

Smallest production design:

```ts
// application/create-invoice.ts
export type CreateInvoiceCommand = {
  orderId: string;
};

export type CreateInvoiceResult = {
  invoiceId: string;
  totalCents: number;
};

export type OrderForInvoicing = {
  id: string;
  status: "APPROVED" | "PENDING" | "CANCELLED";
  lines: Array<{ amountCents: number }>;
};

export type InvoiceDraft = {
  orderId: string;
  totalCents: number;
};

export interface LoadOrderForInvoicing {
  load(orderId: string): Promise<OrderForInvoicing>;
}

export interface SaveInvoice {
  save(draft: InvoiceDraft): Promise<{ id: string }>;
}

export class CreateInvoice {
  constructor(
    private readonly orders: LoadOrderForInvoicing,
    private readonly invoices: SaveInvoice,
  ) {}

  async execute(command: CreateInvoiceCommand): Promise<CreateInvoiceResult> {
    const order = await this.orders.load(command.orderId);

    if (order.status !== "APPROVED") {
      throw new OrderNotApprovedError(order.id);
    }

    const totalCents = order.lines.reduce((sum, line) => sum + line.amountCents, 0);
    const invoice = await this.invoices.save({ orderId: order.id, totalCents });

    return { invoiceId: invoice.id, totalCents };
  }
}

export class OrderNotApprovedError extends Error {
  constructor(orderId: string) {
    super(`Order ${orderId} is not approved`);
  }
}
```

Ownership:
- The application layer owns `CreateInvoiceCommand`, `CreateInvoiceResult`, `OrderForInvoicing`, and `InvoiceDraft` because those are the use case contract and the exact data it needs.
- Prisma types stay in infrastructure. Next.js types stay in the web adapter.

Where translation happens:
- Next.js route translates HTTP input to `CreateInvoiceCommand`, calls the use case, then translates `CreateInvoiceResult` or `OrderNotApprovedError` to HTTP JSON.
- Prisma adapters translate database rows into `OrderForInvoicing` and translate `InvoiceDraft` into Prisma `create` data.

Concrete wiring belongs in the outer layer:

```ts
// app/api/invoices/route.ts
import type { NextRequest } from "next/server";
import { NextResponse } from "next/server";
import { prisma } from "@/infrastructure/prisma";
import {
  CreateInvoice,
  OrderNotApprovedError,
} from "@/application/create-invoice";
import {
  PrismaOrderReader,
  PrismaInvoiceWriter,
} from "@/infrastructure/invoicing";

export async function POST(request: NextRequest): Promise<NextResponse> {
  const useCase = new CreateInvoice(
    new PrismaOrderReader(prisma),
    new PrismaInvoiceWriter(prisma),
  );

  try {
    const result = await useCase.execute({
      orderId: request.nextUrl.searchParams.get("orderId")!,
    });

    return NextResponse.json(
      { id: result.invoiceId, totalCents: result.totalCents },
      { status: 201 },
    );
  } catch (error) {
    if (error instanceof OrderNotApprovedError) {
      return NextResponse.json({ error: "not approved" }, { status: 409 });
    }
    throw error;
  }
}
```

```ts
// infrastructure/invoicing.ts
import type { PrismaClient } from "@prisma/client";
import type {
  LoadOrderForInvoicing,
  OrderForInvoicing,
  SaveInvoice,
  InvoiceDraft,
} from "@/application/create-invoice";

export class PrismaOrderReader implements LoadOrderForInvoicing {
  constructor(private readonly prisma: PrismaClient) {}

  async load(orderId: string): Promise<OrderForInvoicing> {
    const order = await this.prisma.order.findUniqueOrThrow({
      where: { id: orderId },
      include: { lines: true },
    });

    return {
      id: order.id,
      status: order.status,
      lines: order.lines.map((line) => ({ amountCents: line.amountCents })),
    };
  }
}

export class PrismaInvoiceWriter implements SaveInvoice {
  constructor(private readonly prisma: PrismaClient) {}

  async save(draft: InvoiceDraft): Promise<{ id: string }> {
    const invoice = await this.prisma.invoice.create({ data: draft });
    return { id: invoice.id };
  }
}
```

That is the smallest design that keeps the approval rule and invoice-creation action independent from both Next.js and Prisma while still making translation and wiring explicit.

